help for obscure Linux tasks/configs, and other software found along the way

fc-list shows what fonts are installed (FontConfig?)

sway crashed with "assertion failed"? try
sway -V # verbose
might see something about /run/user
check if /run/user/$(id -u) exists as it should, and if not
sudo mkdir /run/user/$(id -u)
sudo chown $(whoami) !$

man pages/apropos index out-of-date/missing something?
sudo makewhatis /usr/share/man

list explicitly-installed packages (not just dependencies) under Void's XBPS:
xbps-query -m

make adb (Android Debug Bridge) work for regular non-root users:
- make /etc/udev/rules.d/51-android.rules as follows
SUBSYSTEM=="usb", ATTR{idVendor}=="VENDOR_ID", MODE="0660", GROUP="plugdev"
    where you fill in VENDOR_ID according to the first half of the ID field from lsusb
- reload udev with
    sudo udevadm control --reload
    sudo udevadm trigger
- add self to plugdev group
    sudo usermod -aG plugdev $USER

Vim's 'tabstop' is the width of the TAB character, not the width of a space-indent
'shiftwidth' is what you seek for general indent-width

~user is home directory of arbitrary user

uni search QUERY
is a great way to find Unicode characters, in place of my ucc

string match -r '%d.*' $name
doesn't work because the regexp dialect of fish's string-match doesn't have %d

flatpak info --show-permissions app.domain.name
to show what directories a Flatpak app has access to
flatpak override --user --filesystem=DESCRIPTION app.domain.name
to add access to more such directories

mkdir -p /mnt/{boot,home}
expands by alternation in braces to
mkdir -p /mnt/boot /mnt/home

to convert caps-lock to something more useful, i run
sudo rc-update add udevmon default
to register a service "udevmon" under OpenRC, with
sudo rc-service udevmon restart
to start it, where the service is defined in
/etc/init.d/udevmon
a text file similar to peers in its same directory, but simpler, which runs
/usr/bin/udevmon -c /etc/interception/udevmon.d/caps2esc.yaml
which caps2esc.yaml is based around the command
intercept -g $DEVNODE | caps2esc | uinput -d $DEVNODE
where intercept and uinput come from interception-tools

pacman -Qo is faster than pacman -F, but only applies to already-installed files

/etc/wpa_supplicant/wpa_supplicant.conf holds network blocks that hold, e.g. for eduroam
network={
    ssid="eduroam"
    identity="user@host"
    psk="password"
    password="password"
    mesh_fwding=1
}
adding mesh_fwding seemed to solve recent connection issues

colours of syntax highlighting in Vim/Neovim are changed by
:colorscheme NAME

WiFi gets soft rfkill'd on each boot? apparently connmand causes this on my machine, so you must somehow prevent connmand from running
i do that by replacing the command in /etc/init.d/connmand

a udev rule can force the monitor backlight to minimum brightness when detected by the udev-trigger service:
ACTION=="add", SUBSYSTEM=="backlight", KERNEL=="acpi_video0", RUN+="/bin/sh -c 'echo 0 > /sys/class/backlight/acpi_video0/brightness'"
put that in /etc/udev/rules.d/90-backlight.rules and try it with
sudo rc-service udev-trigger restart

animations too slow in LibreWolf/Firefox? go to about:config, search for "animation", and change options like sidebar.animation.expand-on-hover.duration-ms

Ctrl+Y in Neovim serves to pick the first autocomplete option, more effective than the multi-step Tab -> Shift-Tab

loginctl suspend
from elogind, works to suspend (sleep to mem) your system without root access, like an easier
echo mem >/sys/power/state

POSIX sh's test command includes the form [ A -nt B ], for "file A newer than file B"
it treats files that don't exist as older than any file that does exist, but all files that don't exist are of equal age

Android's adb shell uses Toybox (BusyBox knockoff) for coreutils, of which touch -d is broken in parsing datetimes, but at least adb push seems to copy modification times as hoped

fetch content for a git submodule that starts empty/blank with
git submodule update --init

adb shell pm uninstall --user 0 TLD.DOMAIN.APPNAME
should uninstall/remove an app from Android over adb command line, we'll see if it persists across phone restarts

networking (wpa_supplicant, dhcpcd, etc) doesn't start automatically because those services aren't in any OpenRC runlevel, to fix:
sudo rc-update add chrony default
sudo rc-update add wpa_supplicant default

you can preview/show a TTF font file without installing via ImageMagick:
display font.ttf

PipeWire audio depends on processes pipewire, pipewire-pulse, and wireplumber, serviced for OpenRC under respective files of /etc/user/init.d/
rc-update --user add pipewire

list input devices under Sway (Wayland) with
swaymsg -t get_inputs
this gives JSON if led anywhere other than the immediate terminal, so you can filter it with e.g.
swaymsg -t get_inputs | jq '.[] | select(.type == "keyboard")'

setup a CUPS printer for lpr, given IP address
sudo lpadmin -p printername -v ipp://1.2.3.4 -m everywhere

external speakers via headphone jack stopped working, found that the issue was on the computer, not the speakers, fixed with ALSA command while speakers plugged in
sudo alsactl restore

input device on bus 0x11, vendor 0x2, product 0x8, version 0x300 is "AlpsPS/2 ALPS DualPoint TouchPad" which gives input events for absolute finger position on laptop trackpad
this is a surprise tool that will help us later

burn an ISO (such as Linux installer) to a flash drive /dev/sdb with (very slow on my machine, such as 2 MB/s)
sudo dd if=target.iso of=/dev/sdb
notably use /dev/sdb (the whole drive) and not /dev/sdb1 (a partition), for if you write to just a partition, it's not bootable as intended, and yields an error such as "Selected boot device failed"

to use Neovim's native LSP client, put Lua config files in ~/.config/nvim/lsp/ as written in e.g.
https://github.com/neovim/nvim-lspconfig

scanimage on my machine has a long delay (~8 s) before any scanning, or even showing backend info, which is fixed by specifying the device in the command line, as
scanimage -d escl:http://192.168.0.11:80

zram is a Linux kernel feature for compressed swap-like space in DRAM, which i set up (yet to see if it actually helps) with
sudo modprobe zram
sudo zramctl -fs 1GiB
sudo mkswap /dev/zram0
sudo swapon /dev/zram0

Intel i5 M 520 has Westmere microarchitecture of 2010, and cannot run OpenGL 3 or Vulkan

to compile and run code to Arduino Nano:
arduino-cli sketch new sketch_name
arduino-cli upload -b arduino:avr:nano -p /dev/ttyUSB0
to write to /dev/ttyUSB0, you must be in uucp group (apparently dialout on other machines)

loginctl suspend via laptop lid close has been very laggy on my machine, but inconsistently and (it appeared) only after the system was up for a long time
preliminarily: time since last resume + lag from new lid-close to actual suspend = 30 s + epsilon, which 30 s figure causally matches loginctl's HoldoffTimeoutSec parameter, which is apparently a feature, not a bug (see elogind documentation)
ChatGPT tells me the point of that is to handle the (rare for me) situation that i dock the laptop while it's closed/suspended, resume it, and close it again quickly, before elogind can detect the docking and change its behaviour
